%N A307865 a(n) is the number of natural bases b < 2n+1 such that b^n == -1 (mod 2n+1).
%C A307865 For n > 0, a(n) = n if and only if 2n+1 is prime.
%C A307865 Note that a(n) < n if and only if 2n+1 is composite.
%C A307865 Conjecture: if 2n+1 is an absolute Euler pseudoprime, then a(n) = 0.
%C A307865 This was proved by an autonomous AI agent, see the Lean file. The proof uses the fact that every odd composite m is either a prime power p^k or a coprime product A * B. The prime-power case derives a contradiction from a nilpotent element (1+y)^n = 1+ny; the coprime case builds a Chinese Remainder Theorem unit that can't satisfy plus or minus 1. - _Ralf Stephan_, Jun 01 2026
%H A307865 Google Deepmind, <a href="https://github.com/google-deepmind/alphaproof-nexus-results/blob/main/APNOutputs/OEIS/oeis_307865_conjecture_0.lean">AlphaProof Nexus: A307865 Lean file</a>
%t A307865 a[n_] := Length[Select[Range[2n], PowerMod[#, n, 2n+1] == 2n &]]; Array[a, 100] (* _Amiram Eldar_, May 02 2019 *)
%o A307865 (PARI) a(n) = sum(b=1, 2*n, Mod(b, 2*n+1)^n == -1); \\ _Michel Marcus_, May 02 2019
